<td><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></td></tr></table><pre itemprop="articleBody"><br /><br />On Wed, 27 Dec 2000, Rik van Riel wrote:<br />&gt; <br />&gt; The (trivial) patch below should fix this problem.<br /><br />It must be wrong.<br /><br />If we have a dirty page on the LRU lists, that page _must_ have a mapping.<br /><br />What semantics would you say a non-mapped page has? What are the LRU<br />routines supposed to do with such a page? <br /><br />The bug is somewhere else, and your patch is just papering it over. We<br />should not have a page without a mapping on the LRU lists in the first<br />place, except if the page has anonymous buffers (and such a page cannot<br />legally be dirty as things are in the standard kernel - Chris Mason has<br />been working on stuff that would make that a normal thing, but it would<br />also make the page have a mapping).<br /><br />We'd better add a debug check that makes sure that we don't have<br />non-mapped non-buffer pages on the LRU lists, and figure out how such a<br />thing could happen.<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br />-<br />To unsubscribe from this list: send the line "unsubscribe linux-kernel" in<br />the body of a message to majordomo&#64;vger.kernel.org<br />Please read the FAQ at <a href="http://www.tux.org/lkml/">http://www.tux.org/lkml/</a><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
